<DOC><DOCNO> AP880528-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0742EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w PM-Summit-SovietsINF     05-28 0197</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Summit-Soviets INF,200</SECOND><HEAD>Supreme Soviet Called Into Session to Ratify Treaty</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Soviet, the Kremlin's nominalparliament, was called into special session today to ratify theU.S.-Soviet treaty banning intermediate and shorter range nuclearmissiles.   The session came a day after the U.S. Senate overwhelminglyapproved the document and appeared aimed at securing approval ofthe treaty before the arrival Sunday of President Reagan.   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev are expected toformally exchange final copies of the document in Moscow onWednesday.   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told hiscolleagues on the lawmaking body at the start of the session thatthe Soviet Union was not responding to pressure from the UnitedStates and that the treaty would free both countries' resources forpeaceful uses.   A Foreign Ministry briefing for reporters at the summit presscenter was abruptly canceled and journalists were informed that theSupreme Soviet was meeting.   Friday the U.S. Senate voted 93-5 to approve the first armstreaty between the superpowers in 16 years.   Earlier today, the head of the Soviet Peace Committee welcomedthe U.S. Senate's approval and predicted Soviet ratification wouldfollow shortly.</TEXT></DOC>